**ANNOUNCEMENT/HEADS-UP FOR MINERS:**

In preparation for launching the product built on SN1, we will make a few key changes to the subnetwork which we'd like to give you a heads-up for. The release of these changes will likely be early next week.

**Time penalty for Inference:** We will be rewarding early tokens higher than later tokens, meaning you should optimize your code to achieve higher Tokens/Second and make sure you send tokens over as they are being generated. Some miners currently simply batch the whole respond and send it at the end, which will incur worse scores. The exact mechanism is that for (deterministic) inference, a linear decay from 1 -> 0 over the course of the timeout limit is applied. Each token will be scored based on when it is received by the validator. We then take the average score over all sent tokens and award this as the overall score. Concretely, if the timeout is 10 seconds and you send a token at second 1, 4, and 7 you'd receive a score of ((1-1/10)+(1-4/10)+(1-7/10))/3 = (0.9+0.6+0.3)/3 = 1.8/3 = 0.6. If all tokens would have been send at the end and sent jointly with the last token, the score would only have been 0.3.

**Web Retrieval Changes:** There are 3 changes to the web retrieval task:
1) You will have to return more than one single result. We will be sending over a target number of results (e.g. 5) and you will be required to send over 5 disting websites. Your score will be the mean vector similarity to the search query for all websites.
2) Variable time limit: We are introducing a variable time limit (3-20 seconds). The time limit will be sent over for each web retrieval task in the request headers. This allows us to be able to balance speed vs quality in the product.
3) Revised scoring: The overall scoring will remain unchanged (similarity to search query), but some details get revised to be more robust. Currently well-scoring solutions should still score well.

PS: As far as we can tell, OTF is now scoring accurately
